OpenAI API Updates
------------------

From OpenAI ( https://openai.com/index/new-tools-for-building-agents/ ) :

Today, we=E2=80=99re releasing the first set of building blocks that will h=
elp developers and enterprises build useful and reliable agents. We view ag=
ents as systems that independently accomplish tasks on behalf of users. Ove=
r the past year, we=E2=80=99ve introduced new model capabilities =E2=80=94 =
such as advanced reasoning, multimodal interactions, and new safety techniq=
ues =E2=80=94 that have laid the foundation for our models to handle the co=
mplex, multi-step tasks required to build agents. However, customers have s=
hared that turning these capabilities into production-ready agents can be c=
hallenging, often requiring extensive prompt iteration and custom orchestra=
tion logic without sufficient visibility or built-in support.

To address these challenges, we=E2=80=99re launching a new set of APIs and =
tools specifically designed to simplify the development of agentic applicat=
ions:

* The new Responses API ( https://platform.openai.com/docs/quickstart?api-m=
ode=3Dresponses ) , combining the simplicity of the Chat Completions API wi=
th the tool use capabilities of the Assistants API for building agents
* Built-in tools including web search ( https://platform.openai.com/docs/gu=
ides/tools-web-search ) , file search ( https://platform.openai.com/docs/gu=
ides/tools-file-search ) , and computer use ( https://platform.openai.com/d=
ocs/guides/tools-computer-use )
* The new Agents SDK ( https://platform.openai.com/docs/guides/agents ) to =
orchestrate single-agent and multi-agent workflows
* Integrated observability tools ( https://platform.openai.com/docs/guides/=
agents#orchestration ) to trace and inspect agent workflow execution

These new tools streamline core agent logic, orchestration, and interaction=
s, making it significantly easier for developers to get started with buildi=
ng agents. Over the coming weeks and months, we plan to release additional =
tools and capabilities to further simplify and accelerate building agentic =
applications on our platform=E2=80=A6

The Responses API is designed for developers who want to easily combine Ope=
nAI models and built-in tools into their apps, without the complexity of in=
tegrating multiple APIs or external vendors. The API also makes it easier t=
o store data on OpenAI so developers can evaluate agent performance using f=
eatures such as tracing and evaluations. As a reminder, we do not train our=
 models on business data by default, even when the data is stored on OpenAI=
. The API is available to all developers starting today and is not charged =
separately=E2=80=94tokens and tools are billed at standard rates specified =
on our pricing page=E2=81=A0. Check out the Responses API quickstart guide=
=E2=81=A0 to learn more.

I think this API release is pretty interesting for a host of reasons.

First, from a developer perspective, this solves one of the biggest pain po=
ints from the Chat Completions API ( https://platform.openai.com/docs/api-r=
eference/chat ) : that API, which has become something of an industry stand=
ard, was stateless, which meant that developers not only needed to maintain=
 the state of a current conversation, but they also had to pass an increasi=
ngly large amount of context back-and-forth to OpenAI to accomplish any mul=
ti-step task, whether initiated by the app or the user. The Responses API, =
on the other hand, maintains state on OpenAI's servers, dramatically simpli=
fying things for developers.

The new tools are interesting as well:

* Web search already existed in the Chat Completions API, but if you wanted=
 to use it you were committed to use it =E2=80=94 a web search would be don=
e before a response was generated no matter what; with the Responses API se=
arch can be invoked on an as-needed basis.
* File search operates similarly: once you have uploaded the files you want=
 searched to OpenAI's servers, the Responses API will leverage them on an a=
s-needed basis.
* Computer use gives developers the capabilities of Operator, OpenAI's brow=
ser-using agent. Unlike file search, however, computer use is just an API; =
OpenAI isn't hosting any virtual machines for you, so you'll have to do tha=
t yourself.

Despite its limitations, the computer use tool is notable because it is del=
ivering the capability that was at the core of a ChatGPT Pro feature that O=
penAI released a mere seven weeks ago ( https://openai.com/index/introducin=
g-operator/ ).

Steelmanning the API Business
-----------------------------

This raises the obvious question as what is OpenAI's priority: its products=
 or its API? This exact question came up on the AMA OpenAI conducted on X i=
n the wake of the release:

( https://x.com/kevinweil/status/1899529369430749567 )

Kevin Weil is the Chief Product Officer of OpenAI, and was a former head of=
 product for Instagram. Instagram is notable for the extremity with which i=
t embraced being a product; the only APIs that exist now are for businesses=
 and creators (even the basic Display API, which is all that was left of th=
e old public API that was shut down in 2018, was itself shut down last year=
 ( https://developers.facebook.com/blog/post/2024/09/04/update-on-instagram=
-basic-display-api/ ) ). Heck, even users are limited to a single link in b=
io!

This is an entirely rational approach for Instagram: they are an ad-support=
ed business that makes more money the more time more users spend in their a=
pps. An API works against both goals: it gives some number of users a reaso=
n to not be on Instagram, and it gives users on Instagram a way to leave. G=
iven that Instagram's addressable market is the entire world (which is a pl=
ausible goal given it is fully ad-supported), there is no conceivable way t=
hat an API =E2=80=94 even if Instagram charged for it =E2=80=94 would ever =
be a profitable endeavor, and that's even before you get to the cost of mai=
ntaining it.

OpenAI, on the other hand, is not an ad-supported business, at least not ye=
t. Their product =E2=80=94 ChatGPT =E2=80=94 monetizes through subscription=
s; its API monetizes through usage. These are by-and-large compatible busin=
ess models, particularly in the overall structure of OpenAI's business.

* OpenAI has three major cost drivers. First, there are its corporate costs=
, particularly R&D. Second, there are the costs of training; while I don't =
know how OpenAI accounts for these costs, to my mind they are a capital cos=
t that ought to show up as depreciation in cost-of-goods sold. Third, there=
 are the marginal costs of inference for its users and developers.
* Very large R&D and capital costs argue for maximizing the number of users=
, so that those costs can be spread out across more users.
* Working in the opposite direction is the fact that marginal costs are a f=
loor for usage; while large fixed costs call for more users, the revenue fr=
om every additional user needs to at least cover the marginal cost of servi=
ng them.

Both subscriptions and usage charges solve for point three: you can ensure =
that all of your users are covering their marginal costs, and then figure o=
ut the price point above that that maximizes revenue.

However, there are a few complications with this simplistic model. First, C=
hatGPT has a free tier which has marginal costs but which does not drive re=
venue. One reason to have this free tier is to be the top of the funnel for=
 new users who might convert into subscribers; figuring out the lifetime va=
lue of these free subscribers =E2=80=94 based on how many convert, how long=
 they are subscribers, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0is a hard problem, but its one t=
hat any business with a freemium business model has to figure out. Another =
reason, however, that is very pertinent to ChatGPT, is the fact that there =
are plenty of alternatives. And, more often than not, these competitive pre=
ssures push the free tier to be overly generous relative to lifetime value.

And, of course, OpenAI is not a normal business: while I assume its revenue=
 easily covers its marginal costs, it does not come close to covering its f=
ixed costs; that difference is made up by investors, with the assumption th=
at, at some point in the future, revenue will do exactly that, and kick out=
 profit above that =E2=80=94 just like Instagram.

How, though, will those revenue numbers be achieved? Well, there are two wa=
ys to increase revenue: increase the number of users, and increase the reve=
nue-per-user.

Here you can definitely see the allure of enhancing the API: first, OpenAI =
is pushing new capabilities =E2=80=94 like computer-control =E2=80=94 down =
to the API sooner-rather-than-later; that should help get more developers o=
n board. Second, OpenAI is increasing the stickiness of its API. Consider t=
he difference I noted above between the Responses API and the Chat Completi=
ons API: the former, by being stateless, is trivial to switch out for anoth=
er model that copied the API (which basically everyone has done). The forme=
r, by being stateful, will likely be trickier to switch out; moreover, that=
 trickiness increases exponentially with every OpenAI-specific tool that it=
 leverages. And, helpfully enough, the subscription business helps drive th=
e development of those tools in the first place =E2=80=94 OpenAI is its own=
 first-best customer.

This approach doesn't just increase API users, and retain them more effecti=
vely, it also increases the likelihood of making more money off of them as =
well. First, to the extent OpenAI's API is better is the extent to which de=
velopers can build better products, which means they will have more success=
, which will drive more usage. Second, the more cross-usage OpenAI can driv=
e of its API, the more usage it is driving overall, increasing revenue.

The Problem With Both
---------------------

The product side is a little trickier. ChatGPT almost certainly has very hi=
gh brand awareness, although I'm sure there are still people trying it for =
the first time. A bigger problem is how many users only ever use the free t=
ier; I suspect one of the reasons people were enamored with DeepSeek ( http=
s://stratechery.com/2025/the-openai-critique-comparative-advantage-and-infr=
astructure-aggregation-theory-and-cheap-ai/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1=
