obably more likely to be aware of alternatives, which helps put a cap on pr=
icing. And now, thanks to this API release, some of the exclusive ChatGPT f=
eatures are going to be available elsewhere.

In short, while its remarkable just how much money OpenAI is making from su=
bscriptions =E2=80=94 at least $25 million in revenue per month ( https://w=
ww.theinformation.com/briefings/openai-revenue-surged-from-200-a-month-chat=
gpt-subscriptions ) =E2=80=94 there are some natural limits, both in terms =
of number of users and revenue-per-user, to just how big a subscription bus=
iness can get, particularly a consumer-focused one.

There is, however, a workaround: advertising. Advertising simultaneously in=
creases your addressable market, by making the product "free", and also unc=
aps your potential revenue-per-user, because it is advertisers footing the =
bill, not users. This is why Instagram is such a good business!

Again, though, it's not so easy for OpenAI. They have marginal costs to cov=
er and zero advertising revenue to cover them; it's also not clear what kin=
d of advertising will actually work with chatbots. It is in many respects s=
afer and easier to, as Weil says, stick with being both a product and an AP=
I company, with business models that are broadly similar.

Those businesses, however, both have competition =E2=80=94 particularly the=
 API. That's going to be another natural limiter. On the other hand, a pote=
ntial ad business (augmented with subscriptions, i.e. The Unified Content B=
usiness Model ( https://stratechery.com/2023/the-unified-content-business-m=
odel/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3=
J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxp=
bmUiLCJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHRwczo=
